steps.description:
This is the simplest method; it is the hand-carried wrap. This method allows you to quickly and easily create a bag for carrying a large amount of food or other products.Tie two opposite corners together over the food or packages sitting in the middle. The cloth should already be covering the items. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6a/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6a/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Pull across the other two corners to meet together and tie. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/81/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/81/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Grab the bag in the middle to carry. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3c/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3c/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

This is a variation of the first technique, known also as the shoulder carry-wrap. This technique allows you to make an ergonomic method of carrying a large amount of food. Place items in the middle of the cloth and tie two opposite corners across the middle. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/dc/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/dc/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Take one of the remaining corners and tie a side knot in it (like a candy wrapper twist). {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fd/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fd/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Tie the other corner in a side knot. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/49/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/49/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Pick up the bag from the middle knot. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/23/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/23/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet4.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Sling it over your shoulder to carry the goods. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5e/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet5.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5e/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet5.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-3Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

This translates as the melon carry-wrap. It demonstrates just how strong a thin piece of cloth can be.Place a 16 pound bowling ball (or your groceries) in the middle of the square cloth. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/84/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/84/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Bring up two adjacent corners and tie together in a large knot. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6f/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6f/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Tie the other two adjacent corners together. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/59/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/59/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Pick up one knot in each hand and feed one knot (A) through the hole formed by the other. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d2/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d2/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Pull up on knot (A) tightening the bag around the bowling ball. Just imagine doing that with an ordinary plastic grocery bag! {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/95/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet5.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/95/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet5.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-4Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

This shows that Furoshiki is not only functional but also decorative. This is a bottle carry wrap. This method will make a great impression on your friends and family, especially when bringing wine as a gift, or to a party.Lay two bottles base to base diagonally across the middle of the square wrap. be sure to keep them about a fist's width apart. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/81/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/81/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Bring one side over both bottles to meet at the other side, forming a large triangle of the cloth. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f4/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f4/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Roll the bottles in the cloth over, like a sausage. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Roll completely until there is no wrap remaining width ways. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f3/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f3/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet4.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Lift the bottles up by picking up the two lengths at the cork end of each bottle. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/98/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet5.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/98/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet5.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Tie the two ends in a knot. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/ca/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet6.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/ca/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet6.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Carry. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet7.jpg/v4-459px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet7.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet7.jpg/v4-759px-Do-Furoshiki-%28Wrap-and-Carry-Things-With-Square-Cloth%29-Step-5Bullet7.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
